@Node "absram.device"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"

absram.device
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
	This device is a replacement of the original 'ramdrive.device'
	which handles e.g. RAD:.
	                           
	Features:
	                            
	- automount with FastFileSystem (DOS\X)	  
	- allows various 'SectorSize's (256 Byte - 32 KBytes)	
	- it can be told to use a specific memory area for the diskbuffer	
	- it does NOT survive a reset. BUT if you use a memory area which 
	  isn't modified before mounting the device again, the contents of
	  the disk will be still there.	  
	- it doesn't cause a softkicked machine to be switched off/on after
	  a crash/reset like an active RAD: does.
 	  
	Why another ramdisk device ?
	~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~	
	The original ramdrive.device uses allocmem to get the diskbuffer.
	This means it uses the next free memory area. If you've got an
	accelerator card with 32Bit ram, this memory is prefered. This
	means the ramdisk uses the 32Bit ram and the programs you start
	after mounting the drive must use the slow 16Bit ram. .......
	 
	How can you tell the device to use a specific memory area ?
	~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
	Since Workbench 2.0, there's a program called 'ShowConfig' in the
	Tools drawer of the Workbench disk. This program can be used to
	examine your machine (what processor, chips, ram, boards...).
	If you have a 16Bit ram card, it can be found in the BOARDS: section.
	e.g. RAM (...) Prod=... (@$600000 4meg Mem). This means you have
	a ramboard at $600000 with 4M ram. If you want to use this board
	for the diskbuffer, you have to set the 'Flags = 0x600000'. The
	0x in front of the address is only another sign for '$' (it means
	the value is a HEX-value).
	If you have 2M of chipmem, you can use the upper 1M for the disk
	buffer (Flags = 0x100000), too. If you know how to calcuate a hex
	number, you can set the diskbuffer at the end of a ramboard, too.
	e.g. 4M at $600000, a 880K disk at the end of this board means to
	set the Flags = 0x924000. Please note: You can't set the disk at
	the end of the chipram, because this area is (usually) used as the
	system stack.
	  
	How can I change the size of the ramdisk ?
	~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
	It works exactly like the ramdrive.device. You can change the fields
	in the mountlist (SectorSize, SectorsPerTrack, Surfaces, LowCyl 
	and HighCyl). Absram.device allows 4 units, I guess only few people
	have more than 8M of ram, so this should be enough.
	   
	Details
	~~~~~~~
	The device reads the disksize from the Dosenvec. If the Flags = 0,
	AllocMem is used to get the diskbuffer. Is it !=0, then the value
	is interpreted as the address of the diskbuffer. Then AllocAbs is
	used to get the diskbuffer (that's the reason why the name of the
	device is 'absram'). If the buffer can't be allocated at this 
	address, the device tries it again, at a 32K higher address. This
	procedure is repeated up to 128 times (128*32K = 4M). If the
	diskbuffer has been allocated, the dostype is checked. If it is
	not DOS\X, then nothing happens (you have to format it yourself).
	If the dostype is DOS\x (=FFS), then the disk is checked whether
	it is already initialized and if it isn't, it is done.
	    
	     
